## 2. How This Assignment Would Normally Be Completed

Below is the end-to-end workflow for building and running the Docker container.  
Due to environment limitations (Docker not installed locally), the commands are documented for understanding but not executed in this environment.

### *Step A – Create the Dockerfile*
A Dockerfile was written to:
- Use Ubuntu as the base image  
- Install Linux tools (curl, wget, vim, git, tree, ping)  
- Generate a script demonstrating Linux commands  
- Execute that script using the CMD instruction  

### *Step B – Build the Docker Image (Normally Done in Terminal)*

```bash
docker build -t basic-linux-ops 



--Git command used
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Added Dockerfile and README for DevOps assignment"

git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/<your-repo>.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

--Learning outcome
Creating the Dockerfile and documenting the workflow demonstrates automation, reproducibility, and environment consistency—core principles of DevOps.

Linux

The Dockerfile installs Linux utilities and executes commands like:
	•	ls -la
	•	pwd
	•	ping

This reinforces understanding of essential Linux operations.

Git

Uploading this assignment to GitHub demonstrates:
	•	Repository creation
	•	Version control
	•	Tracking and pushing changes

Docker

Writing the Dockerfile provides understanding of:
	•	Images vs containers
	•	RUN vs CMD
	•	Layered image architecture
	•	Packaging and automation
